      "summary": "Dispenza lays the groundwork for this chapter's meditation by describing the body as fundamentally made of light and information as much as matter — citing biophoton research suggesting cells communicate via coherent electromagnetic emissions, not just chemical exchange, and that healthier cells emit more organized light. He then introduces the seven traditional energy centers (chakras) plus an eighth center above the head, explaining that each has its own glands, hormones, nerve plexus, and — because energy activating neural tissue creates mind — its own \"mini-brain\" and consciousness. The lower three centers (reproductive, digestive/relational, and solar plexus/will) govern survival, selfishness, and reactive emotion, while the upper centers (heart, throat, third eye/pineal, crown, and the eighth center) govern selfless, expansive states such as love, truth, insight, and connection to the wider field. When people get stuck in fear, guilt, shame, or anger, their energy tends to lodge in one of the lower three centers, blocking it from flowing upward and expressing itself as illness or dysfunction in the corresponding body region.\n\nThe practice itself — the \"Blessing of the Energy Centers\" — trains people to rest attention narrowly on each center (convergent focus, \"the particle\") and then open attention to the space surrounding it (divergent focus, \"the wave\"), which shifts brain waves from busy beta toward calmer alpha/theta and allows the autonomic nervous system, rather than the conscious mind, to reorganize each center's function. Dispenza reports GDV (gas discharge visualization) measurements from workshops showing measurably more balanced and expanded energy fields around participants' bodies and individual centers after doing this meditation, and describes students reporting resolution of conditions ranging from digestive disorders to tumors. The purpose is to move stuck survival-level energy back into circulation and up through the centers, restoring coherence to the body's several \"minds\" at once.",
